The agri bills are opening doors for the farmers. They're not forcibly pushing farmers through newly opened doors.  These bills would not have any impact on the Minimum Support Price (MSP) mechanism which will continue.  Farmers will be free to sell their produce to anyone. They will also not have to pay any taxes.  What will be affected?  1. The state governments of Punjab and Haryana will be affected most because of loss ‘Mandi Tax’, a good source of revenue.  2. Middle men will also lose their commissions.  Why shouldn't farmers have freedom of choice?  The bill on Agri market seeks to allow farmers to sell their produce outside APMC ‘mandis’ to whoever they want. Anyone can buy their produce even at their farm gates. Though ‘commission agents’ of the ‘mandis’ and states could lose 'commissions' and 'mandi fees' respectively (the main reasons for the current protests), farmers will get better prices through competition and cost-cutting on transportation.  The  legislation on contract farming will, on the other hand, allow farmers to enter into a contract with agri-business firms or large retailers on pre-agreed prices of their produce. This will help small and marginal farmers as the legislation will transfer the risk of market unpredictability from the farmer to the sponsor.  Small farmers, who are unable to reach the mandis, will also get good value for their produce, as private markets can reach their barns.  This is clarified by Govt that MSP will continue.  Those who want to sell on MSP can sell in Mandi, and those who want to sell outside let market determine the price.  Why shouldn't farmers have the freedom of choice to choose the buyers of their products?
